ESCOT Bus Lines made a special delivery to the School District of Manatee County on Thursday.

Diane DeGray and Cindy Kerr dropped off approx. 1,600 school supplies at the Professional Support Center. They were donated by their customers in the Tampa Bay and Southwest Florida regions.

The items included notebooks, pencils, crayons and other important learning tools.

Graduation Enhancement Technicians from the District’s Title I schools were present to accept donations on behalf of their students.

Representatives from the migrant and homeless programs were also there to tell them how much their donation means to their school communities #WeManatee

post_text:
TEACHER'S TRIBUTE | When students entered Mr. Robinson's social studies classroom at R. Dan Nolan Middle School this week they were amazed. A tribute drawn on the wall depicted actor Chadwick Boseman, who recently died following a private battle with cancer.

It took their teacher, who is a self-taught artist, about 45 minutes to complete the incredible sketch using only dry erase markers.

"The kids were shocked, to say the least," said Christopher Robinson. "Some are skeptical that I drew it, but they love it."

Robinson says the late actor was a role model for his young son who likes to wear a mask from the Black Panther film that Boseman starred in. "I was just helping remember this great man's legacy." Thanks for sharing your talents, Mr. Robinson.

#WeManatee

The School Board of Manatee County has scheduled an Emergency Board Meeting for 2 p.m. on Friday, August 14, 2020.

The Emergency Meeting is being called to reconsider Policy 8450 - Control of Casual-contact Communicable Diseases.

The version of Policy 8450 approved by the School Board at last night’s meeting mandates all employees, visitors, and students wear a face mask that covers the nose and mouth while on school property, facilities, transportation vehicle, including school buses and/or engaged in school activities.

The meeting will be held in the Board chambers at the School Support Center, located at 215 Manatee Avenue West, in Bradenton.

The special meeting will be aired live on Manatee Schools Television (MSTV) on Frontier CH. 39 and Spectrum CH. 646. In addition, MSTV will live stream the meeting on their “Watch Live” page on the school district website that can be reached through the following link: https://www.manateeschools.net/Page/3700

By a 5-0 vote, the School Board approved a measure to provide the means for district employees to take antibody tests for COVID-19.

Antibody tests look for the presence of antibodies, which are proteins made in response to infections. Antibodies are detected in the blood of people who are tested after infection; they show the body’s efforts to fight off a specific infection.

Details on these tests and how to obtain them will be communicated to district employees as soon as they are available. #WeManatee

Community leaders joined in solidarity today at Braden River High School to launch a campaign called: Mask Up Manatee!

Superintendent Cynthia Saunders, Manatee County, Florida Government Administrator Cheri Coryea and Dr. Jennifer Bencie from Manatee County Health Dept joined community partners from healthcare agencies, non-profit organizations and members of our business community.

Our efforts are to slow the spread of COVID-19 in Manatee County by encouraging everyone to wear a mask and follow CDC recommendations such as social distancing and proper hand washing techniques.

The #MaskUpManatee Coalition will also inform the public important community issues through social media. Stay tuned.

FLORIDA DEPARTMENT OF EDUCATION APPROVES
SCHOOL DISTRICT OF MANATEE COUNTY'S REOPENING PLAN

Late Tuesday afternoon, K-12 Chancellor of Public Schools sent Superintendent Cynthia Saunders an email announcing that the Florida Department of Education has approved the Manatee District's Reopening Plan.

"I am pleased to report that the plan you submitted provides each of the required assurances," Oliva wrote in the email. "As such, your reopening plan is approved, effective immediately."

Oliva ended his approval email with the following:

"Thank you for your commitment to excellence and innovation in support of student achievement and we look forward to continuing to support your faithful implementation of this plan."

SCHOOL DISTRICT OF MANATEE COUNTY'S REOPENING PLAN

"I am pleased to report that the plan you submitted provides each of the required assurances," Oliva wrote in the email. "As such, your reopening plan is approved, effective immediately."

Oliva ended his approval email with the following:

"Thank you for your commitment to excellence and innovation in support of student achievement and we look forward to continuing to support your faithful implementation of this plan."

The School Board officially approved School Reopening Plans for the 2020-2021 school year at a special Board meeting this evening. As part of that process, the Board voted to open schools for students on Monday, August 17, 2020, a week later than originally scheduled.

The Reopening plans approved by the Board include a five-day, on-campus instructional plan for parents who want their students to return to school full-time; a hybrid schedule where students mix on-campus learning with eLearning Manatee; and an option for parents who want their students to continue full-time eLearning.

Parents need to contact their schools by the end of the day on Wednesday, July 22nd, to let them know what plan they want their students to follow so the schools can set up their schedules and complete their planning.

During a workshop on Thursday, July 9, 2020, the School Board of Manatee County and Superintendent Cynthia Saunders discussed a plan for reopening schools for the 2020-2021 school year. The scheduled start date for the new school year is Monday, August 10. Visit https://www.manateeschools.net/reopen2020 to view the plan for reopening.

For almost two months, District staff have been working hard on back-to-school planning. Also taken into consideration: 21,800 back-to-school survey responses submitted by parents, employees and local citizens; as well as public comments offered during a previous board workshop held on Thursday, June 25.

The School Board will officially vote on the district’s Reopening plan at a special School Board meeting scheduled for tomorrow, Tuesday, July 14, at 5:45 p.m.

If you would like to share your feedback with board members, please visit this link to send them an email: https://www.manateeschools.net/domain/1115

To maintain the safety of our community all families will remain in their vehicles. Families will drive by the demonstration tables where teachers and community members will be distributing free books and literacy materials.

Dr. Suess' The Cat in the Hat will be there too.

Congratulations to School District of Manatee County Food and Nutrition Services and Lakewood Ranch High School for winning the Florida Breakfast Challenge!

The Mustangs increased breakfasts served by 41% in January and February compared to the previous year. That's 24,809 breakfasts served in 2020 compared to 17,557 in 2019.

A new breakfast cart (pictured) allowed staff to serve students who may not have had time to go to the cafeteria before class.

Schools with the largest percentage increase will receive a combination of prizes including cash, equipment and recognition, according to the Florida Department of Agriculture & Consumer Services.

#WeManatee

Early Learning Coalition of Manatee County
June 17 at 10:03 AM ·

All Manatee County families in need of child care financial assistance for children ages 0-12, submit an application for School Readiness funding!

To qualify:
▪️ Parent(s) must be working, enrolled in school, disabled, or seeking employment.
▪️ The total gross household income must be at or below 85% of the State Median Income.

Families interested in applying must log on to our Family Portal, https://familyservices.floridaearlylearning.com/Account/LogOn, and submit a School Readiness application.

If you need assistance, contact the ELC Family Services at familyservices@elc-manatee.org or 941-757-2900 x2200.

Families interested in applying must log on to our Family Portal, https://familyservices.floridaearlylearning.com/Account/LogOn, and submit a School Readiness application.

If you need assistance, contact the ELC Family Services at familyservices@elc-manatee.org or 941-757-2900 x2200.

Superintendent Cynthia Saunders and Early Learning Coalition of Manatee County Chief Executive Director Paul Sharff toured the ELC’s new Mobile Learning Lab for students Wednesday at Manatee Technical College.

The Mobile Learning Lab is a classroom on wheels equipped with magnetic walls, a 60-inch Smart TV, Wi-Fi and mobile hotspot capabilities, air conditioning and customized seating which includes wheelchair access for children with disabilities.

Starting June 29, 2020, the Mobile Learning Lab will travel to childcare providers throughout Manatee County offering STEAM (Science, Technology, Engineering, Art and Mathematics) lessons and other educational opportunities.

post_text:
Superintendent Cynthia Saunders’ statement in response to Gov. Ron DeSantis’ plans for reopening schools:

“I want to thank Gov. Ron DeSantis, Education Commissioner Richard Corcoran and all those who invested their time and expertise in producing the ‘Reopening Florida’s Schools and CARES Act’ document. It provides challenging and comprehensive guidelines for moving our schools through and past the Coronavirus crisis. I like the fact it emphasizes safety first and leaves the ultimate decision on reopening schools to the local districts. I applaud the emphasis on addressing the achievement gap, reading proficiency (especially K-3) and plans for using funding from the CARES Act to help in those areas. I firmly believe the Manatee District is on the right track in terms of preparing for the coming school year and I look forward to working with our students, families, teachers and support employees to get our kids back in our schools.”

post_text:
In April, we visited Michelle Dowell’s BioMedical Science classroom at Palmetto High School.

15 juniors and seniors had just received news regarding their attempt to earn a difficult industry certification from the University of Florida.

The two-part Biotechnician Assistant Credentialing Exam took seven hours and the pass rate is only 54% industrywide.

Ms. Dowell’s class received a 100% pass rate on their first attempt.

This certification has set them on a path to career-readiness. They are now BACE certified.

Manatee Schools Television has their story.

The Food Bank of Manatee, a #PLUSprogram of Meals on Wheels PLUS of Manatee, is partnering with the School District of Manatee County to help feed families during the extended school break amid the COVID-19 pandemic!

We will be providing bags of weekend food each Friday during the extended school break, by following the School District of Manatee County Food and Nutrition Services Mobile Feeding Buses. These bags contain 6 meals to feed a family of five breakfast, lunch, and dinner over the weekend. Quantities may be limited. Please check ManateeSchoolFood.net for updates regarding potential food distribution location changes.

Are you interested in helping? Visit https://mealsonwheelsplus.org/food4families/, for information on critically needed items and donations.

post_text:
HOMETOWN HERO | This is Sarah Shields. She is a traveling Registered Nurse (RN) who is currently fighting a battle to save lives in New York City. It's our greatest honor to thank this 2011 Palmetto High School graduate for serving on the front lines during the COVID-19 crisis.

"Some things impact you forever," a quote that Ms. Shields wrote to accompany a black and white photo of her sitting alone in Times Square. She told us that she's proud to be a Manatee County native. Her dad, a retired teacher from Haile Middle School - and her grandparents served as principals at Palmetto Elementary and Braden River Middle.

Her roots in this community run as deep as the pride we have for this hero! To all of our alumni in this fight - THANK YOU #WeManatee

Amy, Emma and Mike Arrigo

post_text:
UPDATE - Friday, March 20, 2020

To Our Parents, Employees and Community:

We want to remind you there is no school for students this coming week due to the Coronavirus.

Governor Ron DeSantis and the Florida Department of Education have stated that school will not resume for students until Wednesday, April 15th, at the earliest.

Superintendent Cynthia Saunders and district officials have been working hard during spring break to organize and lay the groundwork for providing lessons to students online through our Learning Management system known as Schoology. You will hear more about those plans in the coming days.

The goal is to do everything possible to make sure our students complete a full year of learning, while protecting the health and safety of our employees.

We will keep you updated and we appreciate your patience, understanding and support.

The School District of Manatee County invites all families of students with disabilities and students who are gifted, to the 7th Annual Manatee County Agency Fair and Parent Workshops, on Thursday, March 12th from 5:30 p.m. to 8 p.m. at the main campus of Manatee Technical College, located at 6305 State Road 70 East, Bradenton.

The Agency Fair is a chance to talk to more than 45 local agencies and specialized groups, who can assist with the needs of your child. Additionally, six parent workshops will be available starting at 6 p.m. Topics include: children’s mental health, developing young learners, planning for Post-Secondary needs, growth mindset, benefits of yoga and more. Child care will be available free of charge for parents attending the workshops.

Please plan to join us at Manatee Technical College on Thursday, March 12th from 5:30 p.m. to 8 p.m for an evening of resources, fun, food, and prizes!

post_text:
Manatee Regional STEM Competition winner Madison Burt receives a copy of the “Air Force” from Florida West Coast Chapter of the Air Force Association President Mike Richardson.

Burt, who is a junior at Manatee High School, studied the shape of the eight planetary orbits around the sun, as well as the moons orbiting the planets in our solar system - and correlated them to data predicted by Kepler's equations.

She won "Best in Show" and is eligible to advance to the Intel International Science and Engineering Fair this summer in California.

A second student, Jesse Castner from King Middle School, was also recognized by the AFA chapter for his project "Winging It" investigating how five diverse wing shapes impacted the distance traveled #WeManatee

post_text:
COVID-19 Update - Thursday, March 5, 2020: All of us need to be actively engaged in helping prevent the spread of the Coronavirus (COVID-19), and even the spread of the regular flu and other related illnesses.

One of the ways we can do that is by kindly sharing practical steps to help us develop healthy habits to practice daily. Please help us make sure our students and children are aware of these tips and putting them into practice.

To help with that effort, we've found this video which offers seven ways to help prevent the spread of flu:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qKYjj4VTksI

Let’s also do our best to trust the judgement of the medical professionals at the CDC and Florida Department of Health as they guide us in decision making about how to handle this situation.

If you have symptoms that include fever, cough or shortness of breath, Department of Health-Manatee asks that you contact them at 941-242-6649.

Soar in 4 Manatee
February 27 at 2:57 PM ·

Hello Soar In 4 families!!!
On Wednesday, March 4th from 5 - 7:30 pm our free Soar in 4 program will be offered at 3 downtown locations; the ArtCenter, the Bishop Museum and the Central Library.

The first 50 children to visit the ArtCenter and the Central Library will receive a McDonald's gift certificate and all families will receive free admission at the Bishop Museum.

All the activities are designed to support literacy and classroom learning. So come discover, play and learn together as a family. Soar in 4 events are always free for the entire family.

This LEGO portrait of Martin Luther King, Jr. was a collaborative effort made possible by many students and benefactors.

Students in 3rd, 4th, and 5th grade STEM classes along with students who participate in the 21st Century program and TSA/Robotics worked together to sort, plan, and painstakingly place each LEGO.

It took the efforts of many to make this project a reality.

"At Manatee Elementary, we are STEM. Innovators of Excellence and Builders of a Brighter Future!" -Stacy Goode, STEM Teacher

#BlackHistoryMonth #WeManatee

School District of Manatee County added 29 new photos — with Manatee Education Foundation and 2 others at Bayshore Elementary School.
February 26 at 2:19 PM · Bradenton, FL ·

A history-making performance at Bayshore Elementary this morning.

Members of the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra gave their first performance at a Florida school. They're in Bradenton to play the national anthem at a
Pirates Spring Training game.

Bayshore is one of the only elementary schools in Manatee County which offers violin as part of its music curriculum.

The kids were in awe of the beautiful sounds - and had fun with "Maestro" Pirate Parrot, too!

We thank Manatee Education Foundation and the Pittsburgh Pirates for making this incredible experience possible.

#WeManatee

The School Board recognized February 24-28, 2020 as “Public Schools Week” in America.

Public Schools week celebrates the fact that nine out of 10 students in the United States attend public schools – including more than 50,000 students here in Manatee County.

Pat Barber, President of the Manatee Education Association, received the proclamation from School Board Chair Gina Messenger. #WeManatee

post_text:
Last week School District of Manatee County Food and Nutrition Services accepted the U.S. Department of Agriculture’s Summer BreakSpot Trailblazers Award from Florida Department of Agriculture & Consumer Services.

This award recognizes sponsors that used targeted methods to increase meals served during the summer.

Food & Nutrition Services Department spent the 2019 summer months Blazing Trails by creating new community partnerships that helped roll out an additional new mobile feeding unit called the “Caboose” and hosting a Kids Wellness and Resource Day community event.

These partnerships and event increased the number of meals served helping to further their mission of feeding as many kids as possible during the long summer months. The award was presented by the USDA at the 2020 Summer BreakSpot Summer Partners Meeting held in Orlando #WeManatee

Proud Coaches include: Tamiya McClern, Yovonda Holmes-Shepherd, Ariana Kelly and Keenan Wooten.

Students in Teacher Starloe Galletta’s classroom at Electa Lee Magnet Middle School connected with National Geographic Storytellers who are studying climate change on Mount Everest.

They participated in a live YouTube broadcast today which allowed them to learn more about the treacherous conditions, base camps, Sherpas, weather data and more.

It was an excellent learning experience for our students #WeManatee

Chief Bevan was at Ballard Elementary today to remind drivers to #PutItDown and focus! Texting while driving is against the law. post_text:
Here's an incredible story about how Palmetto High School football helmets will be used to help ICU patients at Manatee Memorial Hospital.

#WeManatee
shared_text:
Manatee Memorial Hospital
January 8 at 4:00 PM ·

Recently, Coach David Marino, Coach Dan Whidden and Xavier Williams and Matt Wyatt, senior football players, presented Palmetto High School Football Helmets to Suzy Blatt, our Intensive Care Unit Director and her staff, for patients with emergent esophageal bleeding. These helmets will be used to secure tubing for ICU patients. Many thanks goes to this team for their thoughtfulness and generosity for our patients. Go Tigers!
